  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds from criminal activities) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers, often involving multiple intermediaries and jurisdictions.\n\nIn China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law was enacted in 2007 and has since been amended to strengthen the legal framework against money laundering activities. The law criminalizes money laundering and imposes strict obligations on financial institutions to prevent and detect such activities. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment.\n\nAdditionally, China is a member of the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an international body that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. This membership underscores China's commitment to adhering to international norms and cooperation in the fight against financial crimes.",
